  "articleSummary": "The article argues that PostgreSQL already provides three complementary search primitives—full‑text search (lexical tsvector + GIN), trigram similarity (pg_trgm), and exact‑match indexes (B‑tree/hash)—and that teams should combine them rather than defaulting to a single tool or an external search service. It explains when each primitive is the right fit (lexical matching for long prose, trigram for fuzzy name or typo‑tolerant lookups, exact indexes for binary‑match fields) and shows how to layer them within the same tables, using a visual “search primitive map” to illustrate the trade‑offs. The tone is a practical tutorial aimed at developers and DBAs who design search features in PostgreSQL‑backed applications, using the recurring metaphor of “matching the tool to the shape of the query.”",
